Biking in the Rain: An Analysis of Temperature on the Bikeshare Business with ARIMA

Renee Aziz, Lauren Seib, and Manuella de Carvalho Rodrigues

2024-05-01

1 Purpose

Capital Bikeshare is a bikeshare company located in Washington D.C.

The purpose of this project is to analyze the dataset below, which ranges from 2011 to 2012, to see how temperature affects the number of registered users.

Ultimately, this will allow Capital Bikeshare and other bikeshare companies in D.C. to think about when is the best time to market their business.

Our project will consist of everything present in the Table of Contents

Data reference: Bike Sharing Dataset on Kaggle

1.1 Objectives

Reading the .csv files from Capital Bikeshare, a bikesharing company in Washington D.C., there is an apparent discrepancy between casual users, users that use the service minimally, and registered users, users that have an account with Capital Bikeshare. As business analytics majors, analyzing business conditions is our passion. We would like to tackle the question of how to turn more of these casual users into registered users through targeted marketing.

Capital Bikeshare’s data set has different variables relating to time and weather. We will not aim to establish which variables cause an increase or decrease in users, but we can hypothesize correlations between variables and changes in the number of registered users.

In addition, we will be using the Readme.txt data dictionary to understand the data from day.csv. We decided to omit hour.csv from our analysis since we think that the hourly data will be too specific for a marketing plan. It is better to analyze trends on a macro level than on a micro level by hour to generate feasible months or weeks to advertise, not hours. We think that overall trends and correlations on a seasonal basis that change daily is much more indicative of a better marketing plan.

We anticipate that correlations we find between the time and the weather might apply to other demographics as well despite differences in location and culture. These results will help identify possible correlations between the weather and the number of registered users, and this is exactly what these companies need for their marketing campaigns.

1.3 Data Preparation and Manipulation

1.3.1 Data Understanding

Capital Bikeshare in Washington D.C., USA, incorporated the bike share data set to monitor and predict the amount of bike rental counts hourly and daily based on the environmental and seasonal factors. They collected the information every day from 2011 to 2012 while users rented the bikes for use.

The data that we will be focusing on in our exploratory analysis is bike shares on a daily basis, which provides 16 potential variables in this data set. While the data set does not have any missing values, one irregularity in the data set is that the data type of the variable ’dteday” is as a character. In addition, another peculiarity is that the data dictionary for this data set incorrectly identifies the seasons. The data dictionary in Readme.txt specifies that 1 is spring, 2 is summer, 3 is fall, and 4 is winter. However, we can see that season 1 is from Jan to Mar 20, season 2 is from Mar 21 to June 20, season 3 is from June 21 to Sep 22, and season 4 is from Sep 23 to Dec 20, until 1 repeats again till the end of the year. I observed this in the year 2011, and just with a quick look at 2012, the cutoff dates for the season are quite similar. Because these dates reflect the seasons in Washington D.C., we know that the date ranges imply that 1 as winter, 2 as spring, 3 as summer, and 4 as fall instead of the season classifications that the data dictionary implies.

1.3.2.1 Useful Variables

dteday Although we do not directly use the date in our analysis, if we wanted to conduct further analysis on the data between a range of dates (e.g., to analyze the impact of an event on registered vs. casual users), then this variable would be essential.

season We would like to see the effects of the season on the number of registered users. It’s possible that a variable associated with season would be more interesting to analyze, however.

mnth It would be interesting to see variation by month instead of just season. This would help us be more specific in our time-series analysis.

holiday Just thinking about a marketing strategy, we know that consumer behavior differs on holidays, especially in regards to transportation, when it comes to time taken off of work for leisure or to spend time with family.

weathersit This variable reports precipitation or weather conditions that would affect bikers like mist, snow, rain, clouds, etc. This is instrumental in analyzing increases and decreases in registered users for this bikeshare service due to utility and demand when the weather is not ideal for biking.

casual This variable reports the number of casual users. It would be intriguing to analyze increases and decreases in respect to the number of registered users.

registered This variable reports the number of registered users which is what our analysis is based upon.

weekday and workingday We think that this reveals a lot about weekly cycles. Weekday is the day of the week ranging from 0 (Sunday) to 6 (Saturday). Workingday is if the day is not a weekend nor a holiday (1) or not (0).

temp, atemp, hum, windspeed These variables represent the actual and feeling temperatures, the humidity from 0 to 100 (based on the summary), and the wind speed from 0 to 67 (based on the summary). We are keeping these variables to experiment with later, but we will not be

1.3.2.2 Variables We Omitted

instant This variable is the index, but our unique key in the data set is the date the length of the data set is the length of the unique values in the date.

yr We already have the date, so this variable is futile.

cnt This is the total number of casual and registered users. We ended up omitting this variable because it is simply the addition of variables registered and casual.

After a data type analysis, the only column that requires modification is the date column because changing it to a date type will allow us to potentially conduct analysis on a range of dates.

1.4 Exploratory Data Analysis

1.4.1 Variable Summary

1.4.1.1 Overview

  • date: Date of the record (character)
  • season: Season of the year (integer)
  • month: Month of the year (integer)
  • holiday: Indicator of holiday (integer)
  • weekday: Day of the week (integer)
  • workingday: Whether or not it’s a working day (integer)
  • weather: Weather situation (integer)
  • temperature : Normalized temperature in Celsius. The values are divided to 41 (max) (double)
  • felt_temperature: Normalized feeling temperature in Celsius. The values are divided to 50 (max) (double)
  • humidity: Normalized humidity. The values are divided to 100 (max) (double)
  • windspeed: Normalized wind speed. The values are divided to 67 (max) (double)
  • casual: Number of casual bike rentals (integer)
  • registered: Number of registered bike rentals (integer)

1.4.1.2 Insights

  • The date variable is stored as Date type and follows the format YYYY-MM-DD.

  • season is represented numerically, with 1 corresponding to winter, 2 to spring, 3 to summer, and 4 to fall.

  • holiday is represented numerically, with 0 indicating a regular day and 1 indicating a holiday.

  • weather has four levels indicating different weather situations. These levels are from 1-4, with 1 describing almost clear skies and 4 describing heavy precipitation.

  • The data set contains a total of 731 rows.

  • Range of Variables:

    • season: 1 to 4
    • month: 1 to 12
    • holiday: 0 to 1
    • weekday: 0 to 6
    • workingday: 0 to 1
    • weather: 1 to 3
    • temperature : 0.0591304 to 0.861667
      • felt_temperature: 0.0790696 to 0.840896
      • humidity: 0 to 0.9725
      • windspeed: 0.0223917 to 0.507463
    • casual: 2 to 3410
    • registered: 20 to 6946

# Compute correlation and its p-value between 'temperature' and 'registered'
cor_test_result <- cor.test(bike_share$temperature, bike_share$registered)

# Extract correlation coefficient and p-value
correlation <- cor_test_result$estimate
p_value <- cor_test_result$p.value

# Print the correlation coefficient and p-value
print(paste("Correlation between Temperature and Registered Users:", correlation))
## [1] "Correlation between Temperature and Registered Users: 0.540011966161786"
print(paste("P-value:", p_value))
## [1] "P-value: 1.44622865127018e-56"

Conclusions:

  • The correlation between season and registered is 0.21, indicating a weak positive relationship; however, registered exhibits a moderate positive correlation with temperature (0.41).
  • registered also shows a moderate positive correlation with month (0.29), which is higher than the correlation with season (0.21).
  • holiday, weekday, workingday, and weather exhibit similar correlations with registered users compared to casual users. Notably, temperature and felt_temperature show relatively strong positive correlations, while humidity displays a weaker correlation.
  • The variable indicating whether it’s a working day (workingday) has a stronger impact on casual users compared to registered users.

Ultimately, we can see that temperature and registered have a strong correlation of around .54. It’s significant since the p-value is way less than .05.

Next, we generated two data frames: one, named “registered_lt_mean,” which will select dates with relatively low registered bike user counts, and the second, named “casual_gt_mean,” which will select dates with relatively high casual user counts.

## Filter dates where the amount of registered bike users is less than the 
## average amount of daily registered users 
reg_lt_mean <- filter(bike_share,
                       registered < mean(bike_share$registered))
## Filter dates where the amount of casuals bike users is greater than the 
## average amount of daily registered users 
casual_gt_mean <- filter(bike_share,
                       casual > mean(bike_share$casual))

Then, we created a function that allows us to view the percentage of bike users, in terms of different variables (season, holiday, and weather) in comparison to the overall occurrence percentage of these variables in the original data set. By calculating and comparing these percentages, we aim to identify any patterns in bike usage behavior.

## Create a function that calculates the percentage of the occurrences in their
## respective dataframe
avg_perc_func <- function(data, column, conditions) {
  results <- vector(mode = "numeric", 
                    length = length(conditions))
  for (i in seq_along(conditions)) {
    condition <- conditions[i]
    filter <- data[data[[column]] == condition, ]
    results[i] <- round(nrow(filter)/nrow(data) * 100, digits = 2)
  }
  return(results)
}

# Function to calculate percentage comparison
calc_comp <- function(data, column, category) {
  avg_perc <- avg_perc_func(data, column, category)
  paste(avg_perc)
}

# Create a new data frame for registered bike users that include the different 
# categories (Season, Holiday, and Weather) and the percentage of registered 
# bike users
reg_data <- data.frame(
  Category = c("Season", "Season", "Season", "Season", "Holiday", "Holiday", 
               "Weather", "Weather", "Weather", "Weather"),
  Type = c("Winter", "Spring", "Summer", "Fall", "Holiday", "Non-holiday", 
           "Clear/Cloudy", "Misty", "Light Snow", "Heavy Rain"),
  Avg_Perc_Registered = c(
    avg_perc_func(reg_lt_mean, "season", 1), avg_perc_func(reg_lt_mean, 
                                                           "season", 2), 
    avg_perc_func(reg_lt_mean, "season", 3), avg_perc_func(reg_lt_mean, 
                                                           "season", 4),
    avg_perc_func(reg_lt_mean, "holiday", 1), avg_perc_func(reg_lt_mean, 
                                                            "holiday", 0),
    avg_perc_func(reg_lt_mean, "weather", 1), avg_perc_func(reg_lt_mean, 
                                                            "weather", 2),
    avg_perc_func(reg_lt_mean, "weather", 3), avg_perc_func(reg_lt_mean, 
                                                            "weather", 4)
  )
)

# Add a new column that calculates the percentage of occurrence of each category
# in the entire `bikeshare` data set for comparison
reg_data$Overall_Perc_Occurrence <- c(
  calc_comp(bike_share, "season", 1), calc_comp(bike_share, "season", 2), 
  calc_comp(bike_share, "season", 3), calc_comp(bike_share, "season", 4),
  calc_comp(bike_share, "holiday", 1), calc_comp(bike_share, "holiday", 0),
  calc_comp(bike_share, "weather", 1), calc_comp(bike_share, "weather", 2), 
  calc_comp(bike_share, "weather", 3), calc_comp(bike_share, "weather", 4)
)

The comparison is important because if the percentage of occurrence in the filtered dataframe is greater than the percentage of occurrence in the original dataframe, this may signify that there is some sort of correlation between that environmental or seasonal factor to the amount of registered/casual bike users on a given day. However, it’s important to acknowledge that further research should be performed, like performing a t-test to ensure that these values are actually statistically significant.

After analyzing these comparisons, we noticed that the percentage of low registered users in the winter is 41.21 % which is greater than the overall occurrence percentage of winter days, which is only 24.76 %. This means that the winter season may be a factor that can affect low registered users.

Furthermore, the percentage of low registered users during the holidays is another disparity that stands out. Among the days with proportionately fewer registered bike users, 4.4 % occurred during holidays, whereas holidays comprised only 2.87 % of the total observed days.

1.4.4 Violin Plot: The distribution of users by season

In addition, we think that a violin plot with a box plot in the middle would be an excellent way to show the distribution of registered users per season while also showing the interquartile ranges and the median. The frequency of the registered and casual users show where the count for registered and count were the most repeated per day. So the median and interquartile ranges would reflect where the user count remained for the most time over the two years: 2011 and 2012.

# Create a longer dataframe that creates a column name user_type with values 
# 'casual' and 'registered' users
bike_share_long <- bike_share %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c("casual", "registered"), names_to = "user_type", 
               values_to = "value")

# Plot the distribution of registered users, by season

We can see that these values are skewed towards the bottom, meaning the median is toward the bottom. This is why we cannot sum the count of users together, the casual and registered, because their skews are different.

More exploratory data analysis can be conducted with these variables. However, we have decided to assume that they would be similar to the results of the weather variable above. If our assumption is wrong, we will disclose this through our process of detrending. They are also not split up into few groups like weather above to analyse.

We can also see that there are outliers where the dots are for casual users. This signifies an unpredictable jump outside of the normal interquartile ranges for this number, and they’re always in the positive direction. 1.4.5 Discussion and Conclusion: Our Hypothesis

In conclusion, we can see that there is clear skew differences between the casual user and registered user data, and there is plenty of seasonality, detrending, and cyclicality to explore.

When it comes to season, there is a clear lower skew on the casual users, disclosing that the median casual users is at the bottom of its range. On rare occasions, perhaps on weekends like demonstrated on the boxplots above, the skew is more central for casual users. Perhaps people are more likely to try out bike services casually instead of registering on the weekends. We can also see a consistent skew for casual users on the weather. However, for both variables, the skew of casual and registered users is lower. This would make sense as people might be generally less likely to ride bikes in poor weather.

Ultimately, we are deciding to focus on registered users since we cannot analyze registered and casual in one call, and the registered users generate more users due to being more signups and subscriptions. All of the above are assumptions. As we progress through a rigorous statistical process, we will see whether or not we can make the above hypotheses and see whether temperature/weather/related variables have an effect on registered users.

1.5 Model Selection: ARIMA

Once again, we picked the bikeshare data from 2011 to 2012 in Washington D.C. This was data recorred by and through a bikeshare company called Capital Bikeshare.

One urgent thought we had was that if the number of registered users on one day affects the number of registered users on another day. In this manner, we thought that ARIMA would be appropriate to run.

1.6.3 ARIMA

reg_resids <- train.ts
train.res.arima <- Arima(reg_resids, order = c(14,0,6))
train.res.arima.pred <- forecast(train.res.arima, h = nValid)

# Set the plot limits
plot(train.res.arima.pred, xlim = c(2011, 2013),  
     main = "Forecasts from ARIMA(14,0,6) with non-zero mean", ylab = "Residuals")

lines(train.res.arima.pred$fitted, lwd = 2, col = "blue")
lines(train.lm.trend.season, lwd = 2, col = "gray")

Here, in our forecast, we can see that the model, the blue line, seems to predict our actual registered value swell. We can see that he blue line is affected by the mean of the actual model, meaning that the noise is diminished in the model. We can also see that the forecasted data seems to be dipping downwards along with everything after 2012.5.

In the actual dataset, the model touches the very bottom prediction interval of the forecast which is a little concerning accuracy-wise.

We must run ACF and PACF again to see if there are more AR or MA components:

par(mfrow=c(1,2))


# Extract the residuals from the ARIMA model
arima_residuals <- residuals(train.res.arima)

# Plot the ACF of the ARIMA residuals
Acf(arima_residuals, main = "ACF of ARIMA Residuals")

# Plot the PACF of the ARIMA residuals
Pacf(arima_residuals, main = "PACF of ARIMA Residuals")

As we can see, there are no more AR/MA components, and our model is final.

1.7 Model Interpretation

Ultimately, the model is accurate but seems to omit extreme errors. The last 4 months of 2012, so September, October, November, and December, are predicted.

In the context of our business problem, we can see that AR/MA components are predictable to a certain extent, and that it’s possible to develop a model from this data. Essentially, the number of registered users on one day will always affect the number of registered users on another day. We can also see that if we want to test correlation and thus AR/MA elements on a different variable in the dataset, like thinking about how holiday or non-holiday affects registered users, we could.

Essentially, from the correlation and with this ARIMA, we can tell that temperature does indeed affect the count of registered users (a positive correlation, in fact, meaning that hotter weather means more registrations and colder weather means fewer registrations), but we can also see that the number of registered users from the previous week may have an effect on the current week.

From a business perspective, this makes sense. If a business service is popular for one week, it will likely affect the popularity of the following week. In this case, popularity is the number of registered users. It also makes sense that consumer demand (or the count of registered users) would decrease when a product may exert some discomfort on the user, like being cold.

Thinking about Washington D.C. in this context, the weather doesn’t get too warm there, so it also makes sense that super hot weather doesn’t exert any discomfort either.

1.8 Prediction and Forecasting

Ultimately, playing with the size of the test data reveals that the more time that’s included, the less accurate the forecast. There seems to be a downward trend with all forecasts which increases their reliability.

shortvalid.ts <- ts(registered.ts, start = c(2012, 43), end = c(2012, 52), freq = 52)

# Converting the training time series to a time series object with frequency 52
shorttrain.lm.trend.season <- ts(train.ts, freq = 52)

reg_resids <- shorttrain.ts
shorttrain.res.arima <- Arima(reg_resids, order = c(14,0,6))
shorttrain.res.arima.pred <- forecast(shorttrain.res.arima, h = nValid)

# Setting the plot limits
plot(shorttrain.res.arima.pred, xlim = c(2011, 2013),  
     main = "Forecasts from ARIMA(3,0,3) with non-zero mean", ylab = "Residuals")

lines(shorttrain.res.arima.pred$fitted, lwd = 2, col = "blue")
lines(shorttrain.lm.trend.season, lwd = 2, col = "gray")

Here, we can see a prediction that seems on-par with our fisst prediction and continues on the downward trend.

1.8.2 Long-Term

#changing the end to 2012, 26 to make it long

longtrain.ts <- ts(registered.ts, start = c(2011, 1), end = c(2012, 26), freq = 52)

longvalid.ts <- ts(registered.ts, start = c(2012, 27), end = c(2012, 52), freq = 52)


longtrain.lm.trend.season <- ts(longtrain.ts, freq = 52)

reg_resids <- longtrain.ts
longtrain.res.arima <- Arima(reg_resids, order = c(14,0,6))

plot(longtrain.res.arima.pred, xlim = c(2011, 2013),  
     main = "Forecasts from ARIMA(3,0,3) with non-zero mean", ylab = "Residuals")

lines(longtrain.lm.trend.season, lwd = 2, col = "gray")

This is quite concerning The model looks really similar in the forecastng as it does when it’s on the actual model suggesting that it’s not being thorough with picking up on nuances. The longer time frame for the forecast means less training data. This all in all decreases accuracy as you can see by not having a nuanced forecast.

1.9 Business Insights

1.9.1 Insights

  1. Bikesharing is more popular with registered users in Washington D.C. in the summer and spring months.
  2. Washington D.C. has nice weather during the spring/summer months - perfect for biking.
  3. There is an AR/MA component within registered users that Capital Bikeshare should keep in mind when thinking about weekly increases/decreases in registered users. More specifically, what exactly caused this increase/decrease from last week’s registered users to this week’s?

1.9.2 Recommendations

  1. Market more during warmer months like summer and spring. This is when the registered user count is higher. People desire bikesharing services more in the summer and spring
  2. Market to college students who have summer internships in washington D.C.
  3. Pair up with companies that offer these internships during the summer months to offer discounts to students in the summer to incentivize more subscriptions and encourage use after the internship as well.
  4. Perform statistical analysis on more variables within the dataset.
  5. Improve supply chain to allocate more resources during the warmer months.
  6. Predict revenues and risks based on weather models.
